data.name: AllMatchesDescription
data.value: Find all the matches in the text or stop after the first match.

data.name: CheatSheetAlternationDetails
data.value: Acts like a boolean OR. Matches the expression before or after the |. It can operate within a group, or on a whole expression. The patterns will be tested in order.

data.name: CheatSheetAnyCharacterDetails
data.value: Matches any character other than newline. Equivalent to [^\n\r].

data.name: CheatSheetAtomicGroupDetails
data.value: Non-capturing group that discards backtracking positions once matched. For example, /(?>ab|a)b/ will match abb but not ab because once the ab option has matched, the atomic group prevents backtracking to retry with the a option.

data.name: CheatSheetBeginningDetails
data.value: Matches the beginning of the string, or the beginning of a line if the multiline flag (m) is enabled. This matches a position, not a character.

data.name: CheatSheetBeginningOfStringDetails
data.value: Matches the beginning of the string. Unlike ^, this is unaffected by the multiline flag (m). This matches a position, not a character.

data.name: CheatSheetBranchResetGroupDetails
data.value: Define alternative groups that share the same group numbers. For example, in (?|(a)|(b)) both groups (a and b) would be counted as group #1.

data.name: CheatSheetCaptureGroupDetails
CheatSheetCapturingGroupDetails
data.value: Groups multiple tokens together and creates a capture group for extracting a substring or using a backreference.

data.name: CheatSheetCarriageReturnDetails
data.value: Matches a CARRIAGE RETURN character (char code 13).

data.name: CheatSheetCharacterRangeDetails
data.value: Matches a character having a character code between the two specified characters inclusive.

data.name: CheatSheetCharacterSet
data.value: A single character of A, b or c

data.name: CheatSheetCharacterSetDetails
data.value: Matches either an A, b or c character

data.name: CheatSheetCommentDetails
data.value: Allows you to insert a comment into your expression that is ignored when finding a match.

data.name: CheatSheetConditionalDetails
data.value:
Conditionally matches one of two options based on whether a lookaround is matched. For example, /(?(?=a)ab|..)/ will match ab and zx but not ax, because if the first character matches the condition a then it evaluates the pattern ab.
Any lookaround can be used as the condition. A lookahead will start the subsequent match at the start of the condition, a lookbehind will start it after.

data.name: CheatSheetControlCharacterEscapeDetails
data.value: Escaped control character in the form \cZ. This can range from \cA (SOH, char code 1) to \cZ (SUB, char code 26).

data.name: CheatSheetDefineDetails
data.value: Used to define named groups for use as subroutines without including them in the match. For example, /A(?(DEFINE)(?'foo'Z))B\g'foo'/ will match ABZ, because the define group is ignored in the match except to define the foo subroutine that is referenced later with \g'foo'.

data.name: CheatSheetDigitDetails
data.value: Matches any digit character (0-9). Equivalent to [0-9].

data.name: CheatSheetEndDetails
data.value: Matches the end of the string, or the end of a line if the multiline flag (m) is enabled. This matches a position, not a character.

data.name: CheatSheetEndOfStringDetails
data.value: Matches the end of the string. Unlike $, this is unaffected by the multiline flag (m). This matches a position, not a character.

data.name: CheatSheetEscapedCharactersDetails
data.value: For convenience, these escaped characters are supported in the Replace string in RegExr: \n, \r, \t, \\, and unicode escapes \uFFFF. This may vary in your deploy environment.

data.name: CheatSheetEscapeSequenceDetails
data.value: All characters between the \Q and the \E are interpreted as a literal string. If \E is omitted, it continues to the end of the expression. For example, the expression /\Q(?.)\E/ will match the string (?.).

data.name: CheatSheetFormFeedDetails
data.value: Matches a FORM FEED character (char code 12).

data.name: CheatSheetGroupConditionalDetails
data.value:
Conditionally matches one of two options based on whether group 'undefined' matched. For example, /(z)?(?(1)a|b)/ will match za because the first capture group matches z successfully, which causes the conditional to match the first option a.
The same pattern will also match b on its own, because group 1 doesn't match, so it instead tries to match the second option b.
You can reference a group by name, number, or relative position (ex. -1).

data.name: CheatSheetHexadecimalEscapeDetails
data.value: Hexadecimal escaped character in the form \xFF.

data.name: CheatSheetHorizontalWhitespaceDetails
data.value: Matches any horizontal whitespace character (spaces, tabs).

data.name: CheatSheetKeepOutDetails
data.value: Keep text matched so far out of the returned match, essentially discarding the match up to this point.For example /o\Kbar/ will match bar within the string foobar

data.name: CheatSheetLazyDetails
data.value: Makes the preceding quantifier lazy, causing it to match as few characters as possible. By default, quantifiers are greedy, and will match as many characters as possible. This behaviour is reversed by the ungreedy (U) flag/modifier.

data.name: CheatSheetLineBreakDetails
data.value: Matches any line break character, including the CRLF pair, and CR / LF individually.

data.name: CheatSheetLineFeedDetails
data.value: Matches a LINE FEED character (char code 10).

data.name: CheatSheetMatchAnyDetails
data.value: A character set that can be used to match any character, including line breaks, without the dotall flag (s).

data.name: CheatSheetMatchDetails
CheatSheetModeModifierDetails
data.value:
Enables or disables modes for the remainder of the expression.Matching modes generally map to expression flags. For example (?i) would enable case insensitivity for the remainder of the expression. Multiple modifiers can be specified, and any modifiers that follow - are disabled. For example (?im-s) would enable case insensitivity & multiline modes, and disable dotall.
Supported modifiers are: i - case insensitive, s - dotall, m - multiline, x - free spacing, J - allow duplicate names, U - ungreedy.

data.name: CheatSheetNamedCapturingGroupDetails
data.value:
Creates a capturing group that can be referenced via the specified name. There are multiple syntaxes for this feature:
(?'name'ABC) (?P<name>ABC) (?<name>ABC)

data.name: CheatSheetNamedReferenceDetails
data.value:
Matches the results of a named capture group. There are multiple syntaxes for this feature:
\k'name' \k<name> \k{name} \g{name} (?P=name)

data.name: CheatSheetNamedSubroutineDetails
data.value: Matches the expression in a capture group. Compare this to a reference, that matches the result. There are multiple syntaxes for this feature: \g<name> \g'name' (?&name) (?P>name).

data.name: CheatSheetNegatedCharacterSet
data.value: A character except A, b or c

data.name: CheatSheetNegatedCharacterSetDetails
data.value: Match any character that is not A, b or c.

data.name: CheatSheetNegativeLookaheadDetails
data.value: Specifies a group that can not match after the main expression (if it matches, the result is discarded).

data.name: CheatSheetNegativeLookbehindDetails
data.value: Specifies a group that can not match before the main expression (if it matches, the result is discarded).

data.name: CheatSheetNonCapturingGroupDetails
data.value: Groups multiple tokens together without creating a capture group.

data.name: CheatSheetNotDigitDetails
data.value: Matches any character that is not a digit character (0-9). Equivalent to [^0-9].

data.name: CheatSheetNotHorizontalWhitespaceDetails
data.value: Matches any character that is not a horizontal whitespace character (spaces, tabs).

data.name: CheatSheetNotLineBreakDetails
data.value: Matches any character that is not a line break. Similar to dot (.) but is unaffected by the dotall flag (s).

data.name: CheatSheetNotUnicodeCategoryDetails
data.value: Matches any character that is not in the specified unicode category.

data.name: CheatSheetNotUnicodeScriptDetails
data.value: Matches any character that is not in the specified unicode script.

data.name: CheatSheetNotVerticalWhitespaceDetails
data.value: Matches any character that is not a vertical whitespace character (line breaks).

data.name: CheatSheetNotWhitespaceDetails
data.value: Matches any character that is not a whitespace character (spaces, tabs, line breaks).

data.name: CheatSheetNotWordBoundaryDetails
data.value: Matches any position that is not a word boundary. This matches a position, not a character.

data.name: CheatSheetNotWordDetails
data.value: Matches any character that is not a word character (alphanumeric & underscore). Equivalent to [^A-Za-z0-9_]

data.name: CheatSheetNumericReferenceDetails
data.value:
Matches the results of a capture group. For example \1 matches the results of the first capture group & \3 matches the third. There are multiple syntaxes for this feature: \1 \g1 \g{1}.
The latter syntaxes support relative values preceded by + or -. For example \g-1 would match the group preceding the reference.

data.name: CheatSheetNumericSubroutineDetails
data.value:
Matches the expression in a capture group. Compare this to a reference, that matches the result. For example /(a|b)\g'1'/ can match ab, because the expression a|b is evaluated again. There are multiple syntaxes for this feature: \g<1> \g'1' (?1).
Relative values preceded by + or - are also supported. For example \g<-1> would match the group preceding the reference.

data.name: CheatSheetOctalEscapeDetails
data.value: Octal escaped character in the form \000. Value must be less than 255 (\377). The syntax \o{FFF} is also supported.

data.name: CheatSheetOptionalDetails
data.value: Matches 0 or 1 of the preceding token, effectively making it optional.

data.name: CheatSheetPlusDetails
data.value: Matches 1 or more of the preceding token.

data.name: CheatSheetPositiveLookaheadDetails
data.value: Matches a group after the main expression without including it in the result.

data.name: CheatSheetPositiveLookbehindDetails
data.value: Matches a group before the main expression without including it in the result.

data.name: CheatSheetPossessiveDetails
data.value: Makes the preceding quantifier possessive. It will match as many characters as possible, and will not release them to match subsequent tokens. For example /.*a/ would match aaa, but /.*+a/ would not, because the repeating dot would match and not release the last character to match a.

data.name: CheatSheetPreviousMatchEndDetails
data.value: Matches the end position of the previous match. This matches a position, not a character.

data.name: CheatSheetQuantifierDetails
data.value: Matches the specified quantity of the previous token. {1,3} will match 1 to 3. {3} will match exactly 3. {3,} will match 3 or more.

data.name: CheatSheetRecursionDetails
data.value:
Attempts to match the full expression again at the current position. For example, /a(?R)?b/ will match any number of a followed by the same number of z: the full text of az or aaaazzzz, but not azzz.
There are multiple syntaxes for this feature:
(?R) (?0) \g<0> \g'0'

data.name: CheatSheetReservedCharactersDetails
data.value:
The following character have special meaning, and should be preceded by a \ (backslash) to represent a literal character: +*?^$\.[]{}()|/
Within a character set, only \, -, and ] need to be escaped.

data.name: CheatSheetStarDetails
data.value: Matches 0 or more of the preceding token.

data.name: CheatSheetStrictEndOfStringDetails
data.value: Matches the end of the string. Unlike $ or \Z, it does not allow for a trailing newline. This is unaffected by the multiline flag (m). This matches a position, not a character.

data.name: CheatSheetUnicodeCategoryDetails
data.value: Matches a character in the specified unicode category. For example, \p{Ll} will match any lowercase letter.

data.name: CheatSheetUnicodeEscapeDetails
data.value: Unicode escaped character in the form \x{FF}.

data.name: CheatSheetUnicodeGraphemeDetails
data.value: Matches any single unicode grapheme (ie. character). This includes line breaks (regardless of the dotall mode) and graphemes encoded as multiple code points.

data.name: CheatSheetUnicodeScriptDetails
data.value: Matches any character in the specified unicode script. For example, \p{Arabic} will match characters in the Arabic script.

data.name: CheatSheetVerticalWhitespaceDetails
data.value: Matches any vertical whitespace character (line breaks).

data.name: CheatSheetWhitespaceDetails
data.value: Matches any whitespace character (spaces, tabs, line breaks).

data.name: CheatSheetWordBoundaryDetails
data.value: Matches a word boundary position between a word character and non-word character or position (start / end of string). See the word character class (w) for more info.

data.name: CheatSheetWordDetails
data.value: Matches any word character (alphanumeric & underscore). Only matches low-ascii characters (no accented or non-roman characters). Equivalent to [A-Za-z0-9_]

data.name: CultureInvariantDescription
data.value: Specifies that cultural differences in language is ignored.

data.name: EcmaScriptDescription
data.value: Enables ECMAScript-compliant behavior for the expression. This value can be used only in conjunction with the Culture Invariant, Ignore Case and Multiline options.

data.name: IgnoreWhitespaceDescription
data.value: Eliminates unescaped white space from the pattern and enables comments marked with #. However, this value does not affect or eliminate white space in character classes, numeric quantifiers, or tokens that mark the beginning of individual regular expression language elements.

data.name: MultilineDescription
data.value: Changes the meaning of ^ and $ so they match at the beginning and end, respectively, of any line, and not just the beginning and end of the entire string.

data.name: RightToLeftDescription
data.value: Specifies that the search will be from right to left instead of from left to right.

data.name: SinglelineDescription
data.value: Changes the meaning of the dot (.) so it matches every character (instead of every character except \n).
